<paragraph id="690C24B821E6E6F1DCE7583E85353184" pageNumber="10">
Remarks: 
<taxonomicName id="FD384E168BEAF64D753597049181E89B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:238387" authority="Deans &amp; Kawada, 2008" authorityName="Deans &amp; Kawada" authorityYear="2008" class="Insecta" family="Evaniidae" genus="Alobevania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Alobevania tavaresi" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tavaresi">Alobevania tavaresi</taxonomicName>
has the most restrictive range of these three species, with collecting events coming from a single locality in Venezuela. This is also the largest species of 
<taxonomicName id="FF180B47CA0031D9A31649292965A629" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:238385" authority="Deans &amp; Kawada, 2008" authorityName="Deans &amp; Kawada" authorityYear="2008" class="Insecta" family="Evaniidae" genus="Alobevania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Alobevania Kawada &amp; Deans" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alobevania</taxonomicName>
, with most specimens measuring up to 3.0 mm in length (head to metasoma).
</paragraph>
